Genomic sequencing

October 7, 2021

This HTML runs through all the steps necessary for analyzing RABV sequence data, specifying necessary input files from external programs. The process assumes use of RABV GLUE sequences as the primary dataset to which additional sequences are added. Steps for adding unpublished sequences are in italics and can be ignored if all of the data used is from RABV GLUE. The primary outputs of this program are the visualization of clade and lineage assignments spatially and basic graphs representing the breakdown of genome regions, partial versus whole genome sequences, and hosts per country.

The steps taken in this analysis are ordered as followed with optional sections marked to be used based on the availability of data and desired resolution and output.

  1. Upload data and identify missing data
  2. Whole versus partial genome sequencing
  3. Initial visualization using RABV GLUE rough clade assignment
  4. Partition sequences based on genome region
  5. Run sequences through MADDOG and format output
  6. Graphical and spatial visualization of lineages at a country level
  7. Preparation of data for regional level analysis
  8. Graphical and spatial visualization of lineages at a regional level

1-Upload data and identify missing data points

First, identify filters that best fit the desired dataset in RABV GLUEs (http://rabv-glue.cvr.gla.ac.uk) sequence database. Download the alignments and metadata for the dataset.Convert metadata text file to a csv. Add metadata of unpublished sequences manually to metadata csv, filling in as much data as is available. For rough clade assignments (alignment.displayName), run the fasta file for each unpublished sequence through the RABV GLUE sequences analysis tool (ADD LINK). Upload metadata csv to script as metadata.

Create a new column and identify each sequence as a whole or partial genome. ## Add variable sorting sequences WGS versus partial sequences

groupdata<-metadata %>%
  mutate(genomeregion = case_when(
    sequence.gb_length > 10000 ~ "WGS",
    sequence.gb_length < 10000 ~ "PGS"
  ))

Process data

Sort data into table of subclade versus country

#Make table w/ column for each subclade (+1 for countries) and a row for each country
lineage_table <- data.frame(matrix(ncol = (length(unique(metadata$alignment.displayName))+1), nrow = length(unique(metadata$sequence.m49_country.display_name))))

# Extract all the different subclades in the metadata, and assign these as column names
x <- c("country", unique(metadata$alignment.displayName))
colnames(lineage_table) <-x

# Add all the countries from the previous step to the "country" column
lineage_table$country<-countries

for (i in 1:length(countries)) {
  country_place<-which(lineage_table$country == countries[i])
  # For each country, on order, find which row of the lineage_table corresponds to it
  lineages<-unique(metadata$alignment.displayName[which(metadata$sequence.m49_country.display_name == countries[i])])
  # For this country, search the metadata and see which subclades have been seen in this country
  # Store this information

 for (j in 1:length(lineages)) {
    country_lineage<-which(colnames(lineage_table) == lineages[j])
    # For each subclade identified in the previous step in order, see which column corresponds to it
    lineage_table[country_place, country_lineage]<-
      length(which((metadata$alignment.displayName[which(metadata$sequence.m49_country.display_name == countries[i])]) == lineages[j]))
    # Count how many sequences in the metadata there are for both the country AND subclade of interest
    # This value is put into the corresponding box in the table
  }
}

# There are many boxes in the table that are NA - a particular subclade isn't seen in that country
# Turn these into 0's
lineage_table[is.na(lineage_table)] <- 0

Extract geographical info

# Add columns to the table ready to be filled in with the Lat and Long values for each country
lineage_table$LAT<-NA
lineage_table$LON<-NA

# If needed, remove hashtag and procede: Remove problem values from the table as there will be no Lat and Long values for these
# Unclear why Grenada is a problem, but this was identified in the cleaning step
#lineage_table<-lineage_table[-c(which(lineage_table$country == "-")),]
#lineage_table<-lineage_table[-c(which(lineage_table$country == "Grenada")),]

# For each country in the lineage table, search for it in the 'world' map object we created earlier
# Find the corresponding polygon (spatial info is stored!) for the country
# The labpt option in the polygon contains the lat and long values in a single vector
# Therefore, these need to be indexed ([1] and [2])
# The values are then put in the corresponding LAT and LON columns
for (i in 1:length(lineage_table$country)) {
  lineage_table$LAT[i]<-world@polygons[which(world$admin == lineage_table$country[i])][[1]]@labpt[2]
  lineage_table$LON[i]<-world@polygons[which(world$admin == lineage_table$country[i])][[1]]@labpt[1]
}

Process data to be read into maps.

#Count number of rows (countries) in the table
n<- nrow(lineage_table)
#Add a column that gives a number to each country
lineage_table$region <- factor(1:n)
# Add a column called "radius" which will be filled with information about the number of sequences
# This is so the size of the pies corresponds to the number of sequences
lineage_table$radius<-NA
# For each country, count the total number of sequences across all subclades
# Enter this information into the radius column
# The sum index looks a little odd; this is because we don't want to include the LAT, LON, region and radius values
# Therefore, we want to only use the columns that are for lineages
for (i in 1:length(lineage_table$country)) {
  lineage_table$radius[i]<-sum(lineage_table[i,2:(1+length(unique(metadata$alignment.displayName)))])
}

# Some of these radii are BIG; these would result in pies bigger than the map!
# Therefore, edit this so those with more sequences are larger, but reasonably sized
lineage_table$radius[which(lineage_table$radius %in% 6:10)]<-6
lineage_table$radius[which(lineage_table$radius %in% 11:20)]<-7
lineage_table$radius[which(lineage_table$radius %in% 21:50)]<-8
lineage_table$radius[which(lineage_table$radius %in% 51:100)]<-9
lineage_table$radius[which(lineage_table$radius %in% 101:200)]<-10
lineage_table$radius[which(lineage_table$radius > 200)]<-11

# Now we've settled on values, divide them all to make them small enough to look nice
lineage_table$radius<-lineage_table$radius/2
print(lineage_table)

Create world map to be plotted on with data

  ggplot(data = world) +
  geom_sf() 
plot

Plot datapoints from lineage_table onto world map using geom_scatterpie. Spatial mapping uses longitude, latitude, and region and radius (defined in the lineage table).

# We also tell it what the names of the different elements in the pies are (the subclades)
plot_world<-plot + geom_scatterpie(aes(x=LON, y=LAT, group=region, r=radius),
                                   data=lineage_table, cols=c(colnames(lineage_table)[2:(1+length(unique(metadata$alignment.displayName)))]), color=NA, alpha=.8)

plot_world

If the analysis is conducted using data from a smaller regional area than is shown with the world map, this step can zoom the map in on using the xlim and ylim functions in the last line of this code block. Choose values based on the boundaries of the data shown in the world map.

# Some of the areas are difficult to see clearly on the world map, so we can zoom in with an extra argument
# We can also adjust the radii to be smaller so it's easier to distinguish countries when we zoom in
lineage_table$radius<-lineage_table$radius/1.5

plot_zoom<-plot + geom_scatterpie(aes(x=LON, y=LAT, group=region, r=radius),
                                  data=lineage_table, cols=c(colnames(lineage_table)[2:(1+length(unique(metadata$alignment.displayName)))]), color=NA, alpha=.8,)+
  coord_sf(xlim = c(90,130), ylim = c(-5,25))

plot_zoom

4- Partition sequences based on genome region

*Note: code included at end of script since not utilized to demonstrate WGS process.Available in published GitHub repository: https://github.com/boydorr/SEA-RABV_genSurv

In order to run sequences through MADDOG (https://github.com/KathrynCampbell/MADDOG), datasets need to be partitioned into genome region.

5- MADDOG

Upload sequence data and associated metadata to MADDOG command line for each genome region selected for analysis. Combine lineage given in sequence information output file with metadata file and upload to R. (https://github.com/KathrynCampbell/MADDOG)

For the rest of the code, WGS data will be used to demonstrate the process. During the MADDOG process, metadata must be re-labelled as date, country, and ID.

Processing data: Table with each subclade and row for each location

# Make a table with a column for each subclade (+1 for areas) and a row for each area
lineage_table <- data.frame(matrix(ncol = (length(unique(metadata$lineage))+1), nrow = length(areas)))

# Extract all the different subclades in the metadata, and assign these as column names
x <- c("area", unique(metadata$lineage))
colnames(lineage_table) <- x

# Add all the areas from the previous step to the "area" column
lineage_table$area<-areas

for (i in 1:length(areas)) {
  country_place<-which(lineage_table$area == areas[i])
  # For each area, on order, find which row of the lineage_table corresponds to it
  lineages<-unique(metadata$lineage[which(metadata$location == areas[i])])
  # For this area, search the metadata and see which subclades have been seen in this area
  # Store this information
  
  for (j in 1:length(lineages)) {
    country_lineage<-which(colnames(lineage_table) == lineages[j])
    # For each subclade identified in the previous step in order, see which column corresponds to it
    lineage_table[country_place, country_lineage]<-
      length(which((metadata$lineage[which(metadata$location == areas[i])]) == lineages[j]))
    # Count how many sequences in the metadata there are for both the area AND subclade of interest
    # This value is put into the corresponding box in the table
  }
}

# The labpt option in the polygon contains the lat and long values in a single vector
# Therefore, these need to be indexed ([1] and [2])
# The values are then put in the corresponding LAT and LON columns
for (i in 1:length(lineage_table$area)) {
   lineage_table$LAT[i]<-shape_region@polygons[which(shape_region@data$NAME_1 == lineage_table$area[i])][[1]]@labpt[2]
   lineage_table$LON[i]<-shape_region@polygons[which(shape_region@data$NAME_1 == lineage_table$area[i])][[1]]@labpt[1]
}

Process data to be read by maps

# Count the number of rows (areas) in the table
n <- nrow(lineage_table)
# Add a column that gives a number to each country
lineage_table$region <- factor(1:n)
# Add a column called "radius" which will be filled with information about the number of sequences
# This is so the size of the pies corresponds to the number of sequences
lineage_table$radius<-NA
# For each country, count the total number of sequences across all subclades
# Enter this information into the radius column
# The sum index looks a little odd; this is because we don't want to include the LAT, LON, region and radius values
# Therefore, we want to only use the columns that are for lineages
for (i in 1:length(lineage_table$area)) {
  lineage_table$radius[i]<-sum(lineage_table[i,2:(1+length(unique(metadata$lineage)))])
}

# Some of these radii are BIG; these would result in pies bigger than the map!
# Therefore, edit this so those with more sequences are larger, but reasonably sized
lineage_table$radius[which(lineage_table$radius %in% 5:10)]<-3
lineage_table$radius[which(lineage_table$radius > 10)]<-4

# Now we've settled on values, divide them all to make them small enough to look nice
lineage_table$radius<-lineage_table$radius/6

Make maps

# Plot a basic map which we will add pies to
# We specify the shape_region shapefile should be used for the map, as the majority of data fits this
plot<-
  ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data = shape_region, aes( x = long, y = lat, group = group), fill="#69b3a2", color="light grey") +
  theme_void() 
## Regions defined for each Polygons
plot

Make maps

# This adds the pies!
# We are taking the basic map from the last step and telling geom_scatterpie there is data in the lineage_table
# It then uses the LON, LAT, region and radius columns we made in the last step
# We also tell it what the names of the different elements in the pies are (the subclades)
plot_phil<-plot + geom_scatterpie(aes(x=LON, y=LAT, group=region, r=radius/1.5),
                                   data=lineage_table, cols=c(colnames(lineage_table)[2:12]), color=NA, alpha=.8) #need to adjust number of columns map will read based on available lineages

plot_phil
